         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot. Garden ¶ 20/5/64 ¶ Dear Sir. ¶  ¶ I replied to your enquiry about what plants I would recommend for your pasture-ground by last mail. ¶  But as letters may get lost I briefly repeat, th...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">64.05.20d</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Brewer</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">MS 100, William Henry Brewer Papers, Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library, New Haven, Connecticut.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot. Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">20/5/64</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Sir.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I replied to your enquiry about what plants I would recommend for your pasture-ground by last mail.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to W. Brewer, 24 April 1864 (in this edition as 64-04-24a).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> But as letters may get lost I briefly repeat, that in my opinion you have for perennial fodder plants mainly to rely on plants of the northern hemisphere. <name key="Trifolium%20repens">Trifolium repens</name>, <name key="Lolium%20perenne">Lolium perenne</name>, <name key="Medicago%20sativa">Medicago sativa</name>, Bromus (Ceratochloa) unioloides with perhaps a few other Clovers must be, I think your stronghold. But you might with advantage add <name key="Hedysarum%20coronarium">Hedysarum coronarium</name> and perhaps <name key="Cichorium%20intybus">Cichorium intybus</name>. As you desired to try <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">our</hi>
               </seg> perennial grasses I have gathered for you as far as the lateness of the season permitted and have much pleasure in sending you in care of Mr Geo Coppin, who goes probably with Mr &amp; Mrs Kean via Callao to San Francisco, parcels of seeds of <name key="Danthonia%20pilosa">Danthonia pilosa</name>, <name key="Eragrostis%20Brownii">Eragrostis Brownii</name>, <name key="Microlaena%20stipoides">Microlaena stipoides</name>. For <name key="Anthistiria%20Australis">Anthistiria Australis</name> I was this season too late.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the box is also contained a set of the transactions of our R. S.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Royal Society (of Victoria).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> for your valued academy of sciences<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Californian Academy of Natural Sciences, of which M had been elected an Honorary Member on 19 October 1863.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> (5 volumes) also 4 volumes of my own work, which perhaps you will kindly deliver. For Mr Bolander I enclosed a set of moss-plates,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Presumably <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>al least some of the plates that were published later in the year as B64.10.03.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> &amp; 194 sp. of dried plants, for Dr Behr or Dr Kellagg<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Albert Kellogg?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> 184 sp. of dried plants, for Dr Behr some pamphlets, for S. W. Moore Esq 46 larger lots of seeds 159 smaller dito for Mr Walker of the Golden Gate Nursery 46 sp of s[eeds] in larger quantity.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The arrival of M’s parcel was reported under the heading </seg>'Forage plants for California' in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Daily Alta California,</seg>
                     <seg style="">13 October 1864, p. [2]: ‘</seg>The last vessel from Australia brought to Professor Brewer of the State Geological survey, a tin-lined box full of Australian seeds, sent by Dr. Mueller, Government botanist of the colony of Victoria. Among these seeds were six packages of seeds of indigenous grasses or forage plants of Australia.’</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The report continued:</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is known that there is a considerable resemblance between the climate of California and that of Victoria. Many of the plants of each thrive in the other. Australia has immense herds of neat cattle and sheep, which fatten on the indigenous grasses, and there is reason to hope that some of these grasses may thrive here. California is poor in forage plants. Not one of our grasses is strong enough to form a thick sod that will retain its vitality through the summer on the dry plains. Professor Brewer has devoted considerable attention to the subject and so has Dr. Bolander a botanist of this city. Experiments will be tried with these Australian grass seeds to ascertain their value. The introduction of a better grass than any that we now have would be worth the expense of a hundred geological surveys.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.1665in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When the item was reprinted in the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">California farmer and journal of useful sciences</seg>, 14 October 1864, p. 89, an editorial comment was added in parentheses: 'We may differ from our contemporary, for we think we have some of the best forage plants in the world. Of this we shall speak by and by'.</p>
                  <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>If dry plants would prove acceptable to your Academy I will gladly send from time to time some supplies.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">With cordial regards</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd Mueller.</p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Anthistiria%20Australis">Anthistiria Australis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Bromus%20unioloides">Bromus unioloides</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Ceratochloa%20unioloides">Ceratochloa unioloides</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Cichorium%20intybus">Cichorium intybus</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Danthonia%20pilosa">Danthonia pilosa</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Eragrostis%20Brownii">Eragrostis Brownii</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Hedysarum%20coronarium">Hedysarum coronarium</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Lolium%20perenne">Lolium perenne</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Medicago%20sativa">Medicago sativa</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Microlaena%20stipoides">Microlaena stipoides</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Trifolium%20repens">Trifolium repens</name>
            </p>
         </div>
